</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast implant–associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma (BIA-ALCL) is a new provisional category in the 2016 World Health Organization (WHO) classification of lymphoid neoplasms, and its incidence is rising owing to increasing recognition of this complication of breast implant insertion. At a median of 10 years after implant insertion, the typical presenting features are sudden-onset breast swelling secondary to peri-implant effusion and less frequently mass-forming disease. Histologic features comprise pleomorphic cells expressing CD30 and negative anaplastic lymphoma kinase (ALK) receptor, similar to systemic and cutaneous ALK-negative anaplastic large cell lymphoma (ALCL). The effusion-only subtype is generally indolent and curable with surgery, unlike the more aggressive mass-forming disease, for which systemic therapy is advocated. High clinical suspicion and pertinent use of radiologic and pathology modalities are essential for timely and accurate diagnosis of BIA-ALCL. Contemporary imaging techniques including US, mammography, breast MRI, CT, and PET/CT are routinely used in breast disease and lymphomas; however, the unique behavior of BIA-ALCL presents significant diagnostic and radiologic interpretative challenges, with numerous nuanced imaging features being pertinent, and current lymphoma staging and response guidelines are not easily applicable to BIA-ALCL. The authors evaluate available evidence in this evolving field; detail key indications, strengths, and limitations of the panoply of radiologic techniques for BIA-ALCL; and propose multiparametric imaging paradigms for management of the peri-implant effusion and mass-forming or advanced disease subtypes, with the goal of accurate optimal patient care. The authors also predict a future model of multimodal assessment using novel imaging and molecular techniques and define key research directions.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190198">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190198">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1a.jpeg" height="1215" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1b.jpeg" height="1215" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1c.jpeg" height="1215" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1d.jpeg" height="1277" width="1270" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1e.jpeg" height="1277" width="1276" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1f" class="graphic" aria-label="Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. (a–d) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 (a), CD2 (b), and CD4 (c) but negative for CD3 (d). (e, f) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). (e) Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. (f) High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig1f.jpeg" height="1277" width="1154" aria-labelledby="fig1f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1f</span>. Immunohistochemical and histologic findings of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a–d)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy, axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy. After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. At US, a large seroma surrounded the intact right breast implant; diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid, which was ALK-negative at cytologic analysis. Immunohistochemistry slides show that the infiltrate is positive for CD30 <b>(a)</b>, CD2 <b>(b)</b>, and CD4 <b>(c)</b> but negative for CD3 <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e, f)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan, Dublin, Ireland). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the biopsy specimen shows large atypical cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. <b>(f)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows large atypical cells, some consistent with hallmark cells amid neutrophils and eosinophils. At immunohistochemistry, the infiltrate was CD30 positive.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig1f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="US of BIA-ALCL. (a) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy for breast cancer (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). The initial breast implant was exchanged after 9 years; 7 years later, she experienced sudden new marked implant-associated swelling. Transverse US image shows a large seroma with septa surrounding the intact implant (arrow). US-guided fine-needle aspiration yielded cloudy yellow fluid, cytologic analysis of which demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). Transverse US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) at the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. US-guided core biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig2a.jpeg" height="1085" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. US of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy for breast cancer (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). The initial breast implant was exchanged after 9 years; 7 years later, she experienced sudden new marked implant-associated swelling. Transverse US image shows a large seroma with septa surrounding the intact implant (arrow). US-guided fine-needle aspiration yielded cloudy yellow fluid, cytologic analysis of which demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). Transverse US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) at the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. US-guided core biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="US of BIA-ALCL. (a) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy for breast cancer (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). The initial breast implant was exchanged after 9 years; 7 years later, she experienced sudden new marked implant-associated swelling. Transverse US image shows a large seroma with septa surrounding the intact implant (arrow). US-guided fine-needle aspiration yielded cloudy yellow fluid, cytologic analysis of which demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). Transverse US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) at the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. US-guided core biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig2b.jpeg" height="1085" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. US of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after mastectomy for breast cancer (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). The initial breast implant was exchanged after 9 years; 7 years later, she experienced sudden new marked implant-associated swelling. Transverse US image shows a large seroma with septa surrounding the intact implant (arrow). US-guided fine-needle aspiration yielded cloudy yellow fluid, cytologic analysis of which demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). Transverse US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) at the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. US-guided core biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Mammography of BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). Craniocaudal mammogram shows the implant; the mass lesion and peri-implant effusion are occult. BIA-ALCL was subsequently diagnosed."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig3.jpeg" height="1876" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Mammography of BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). Craniocaudal mammogram shows the implant; the mass lesion and peri-implant effusion are occult. BIA-ALCL was subsequently diagnosed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="CT of BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. CT image shows a large effusion (arrow) around the right breast implant with no associated mass component being defined, no local-regional or distant adenopathy, and no extranodal disease according to CT lymphoma staging criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig4.jpeg" height="1394" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. CT of BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. CT image shows a large effusion (arrow) around the right breast implant with no associated mass component being defined, no local-regional or distant adenopathy, and no extranodal disease according to CT lymphoma staging criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI of BIA-ALCL. (a) Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction. She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, implant-associated swelling developed. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a moderate peri-implant effusion within the implant capsule (arrow). Aspiration demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast mass 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated breath-hold volume MR image shows a large implant-associated lobulated mass with a central necrotic area and intense rim enhancement (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig5a.jpeg" height="1086" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. MRI of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction. She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, implant-associated swelling developed. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a moderate peri-implant effusion within the implant capsule (arrow). Aspiration demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast mass 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated breath-hold volume MR image shows a large implant-associated lobulated mass with a central necrotic area and intense rim enhancement (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI of BIA-ALCL. (a) Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction. She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, implant-associated swelling developed. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a moderate peri-implant effusion within the implant capsule (arrow). Aspiration demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast mass 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated breath-hold volume MR image shows a large implant-associated lobulated mass with a central necrotic area and intense rim enhancement (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig5b.jpeg" height="1086" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. MRI of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction. She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, implant-associated swelling developed. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a moderate peri-implant effusion within the implant capsule (arrow). Aspiration demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a right upper inner breast mass 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated breath-hold volume MR image shows a large implant-associated lobulated mass with a central necrotic area and intense rim enhancement (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="PET/CT of BIA-ALCL. (a) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after right mastectomy and axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. Axial FDG PET/CT image from a neck, thorax, abdomen, and pelvis (NTAP) study shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. US-guided fine-needle aspiration of the effusion demonstrated BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a left upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). US showed a mass at the edge of the external capsule of the left implant at the 9-o’clock position. FDG PET/CT image shows that the mass (red circle) is mildly FDG avid."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig6a.jpeg" height="1355" width="1635" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. PET/CT of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after right mastectomy and axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. Axial FDG PET/CT image from a neck, thorax, abdomen, and pelvis (NTAP) study shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. US-guided fine-needle aspiration of the effusion demonstrated BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a left upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). US showed a mass at the edge of the external capsule of the left implant at the 9-o’clock position. FDG PET/CT image shows that the mass (red circle) is mildly FDG avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="PET/CT of BIA-ALCL. (a) Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after right mastectomy and axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. Axial FDG PET/CT image from a neck, thorax, abdomen, and pelvis (NTAP) study shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. US-guided fine-needle aspiration of the effusion demonstrated BIA-ALCL. (b) Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a left upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). US showed a mass at the edge of the external capsule of the left implant at the 9-o’clock position. FDG PET/CT image shows that the mass (red circle) is mildly FDG avid."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig6b.jpeg" height="1355" width="1515" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. PET/CT of BIA-ALCL. <b>(a)</b> Effusion-only BIA-ALCL in a 55-year-old woman after right mastectomy and axillary node dissection, implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. Axial FDG PET/CT image from a neck, thorax, abdomen, and pelvis (NTAP) study shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. US-guided fine-needle aspiration of the effusion demonstrated BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Mass-forming BIA-ALCL in a 29-year-old woman with a left upper inner breast lump 3 years after bilateral breast augmentation (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). US showed a mass at the edge of the external capsule of the left implant at the 9-o’clock position. FDG PET/CT image shows that the mass (red circle) is mildly FDG avid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in Fig 5a). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. (a, b) Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in a) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in b) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. (c) Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (d) Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig7a.jpeg" height="987" width="1202" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5a</a>). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in <b>b</b>) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(d)</b> Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in Fig 5a). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. (a, b) Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in a) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in b) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. (c) Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (d) Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig7b.jpeg" height="987" width="1485" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5a</a>). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in <b>b</b>) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(d)</b> Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in Fig 5a). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. (a, b) Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in a) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in b) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. (c) Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (d) Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig7c.jpeg" height="987" width="1014" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5a</a>). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in <b>b</b>) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(d)</b> Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in Fig 5a). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. (a, b) Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in a) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in b) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. (c) Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (d) Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig7d.jpeg" height="1020" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5a</a>). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in <b>b</b>) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(d)</b> Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in Fig 5a). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. (a, b) Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in a) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in b) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. (c) Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. (d) Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. (e) Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig7e.jpeg" height="1020" width="1456" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection for a 6-cm grade 1 invasive lobular carcinoma, followed by placement of a latissimus dorsi muscle flap and implant reconstruction (same patient as in <a href="#fig5a">Fig 5a</a>). She received adjuvant chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and tamoxifen therapy, and three further reconstructive breast operations were performed. One year after the last breast implant insertion, an asymptomatic lump developed along the lateral right breast. <b>(a, b)</b> Transverse US images show a few ripples in the implant membrane (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the lateral right breast at the 12-o’clock position and a seroma (arrow in <b>b</b>) predominantly within the outer aspect of the right breast. Serous aspirate (330 mL) was sent for cytologic analysis. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows large anaplastic lymphoid cells. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. <b>(d)</b> Axial FDG PET/CT image shows that the right breast implant has an irregular contour and is surrounded by homogeneous FDG-negative fluid (arrow). Small-volume patchy minimally FDG-avid soft-tissue thickening at the periphery of the collection is in keeping with inflammatory features. No metastatic disease was appreciable. <b>(e)</b> Axial gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted high-spatial-resolution MR image shows a moderate peri-implant seroma (arrow) within the implant capsule. The capsule itself has mild enhancement, but no mass component is seen. Focal superficial capsular invasion only was found after complete right capsulectomy. Note that US is a clinically useful first-line test for evaluation of breast implant swelling; FDG PET activity is normally observed as a false-positive finding around the periphery of breast implants (owing to macrophage activity and granulation tissue accumulating FDG); and breast MRI is an accurate technique for evaluating a breast implant, peri-implant effusion, and peri-implant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL with a false-negative PET result in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. (a) Transverse US image shows an effusion surrounding the intact right breast implant (arrow) at the 7-o’clock position. A diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid; cytologic analysis demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (b) Coronal FDG PET/CT image shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. The patient underwent deconstruction of the right breast implant and complete capsulectomy. FDG PET does not allow distinction of benign from malignant peri-implant effusions owing to the low cell density in the fluid, with a false-negative result being observed with lymphoma-involved effusions at PET."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig8a.jpeg" height="736" width="1429" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL with a false-negative PET result in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows an effusion surrounding the intact right breast implant (arrow) at the 7-o’clock position. A diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid; cytologic analysis demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Coronal FDG PET/CT image shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. The patient underwent deconstruction of the right breast implant and complete capsulectomy. FDG PET does not allow distinction of benign from malignant peri-implant effusions owing to the low cell density in the fluid, with a false-negative result being observed with lymphoma-involved effusions at PET.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL with a false-negative PET result in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in Fig 1a–1d). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. (a) Transverse US image shows an effusion surrounding the intact right breast implant (arrow) at the 7-o’clock position. A diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid; cytologic analysis demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (b) Coronal FDG PET/CT image shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. The patient underwent deconstruction of the right breast implant and complete capsulectomy. FDG PET does not allow distinction of benign from malignant peri-implant effusions owing to the low cell density in the fluid, with a false-negative result being observed with lymphoma-involved effusions at PET."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig8b.jpeg" height="1902" width="1020" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Peri-implant effusion BIA-ALCL with a false-negative PET result in a 55-year-old woman who underwent right mastectomy and axillary node dissection followed by implant reconstruction, chemoradiotherapy, and immunotherapy (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1a</a>–<a href="#fig1d">1d</a>). After 9 years, the implant was exchanged; 7 years later, sudden new marked swelling of the right breast developed. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows an effusion surrounding the intact right breast implant (arrow) at the 7-o’clock position. A diagnostic aspirate yielded cloudy yellow fluid; cytologic analysis demonstrated ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(b)</b> Coronal FDG PET/CT image shows a large photopenic effusion (arrow) surrounding the right breast implant. The patient underwent deconstruction of the right breast implant and complete capsulectomy. FDG PET does not allow distinction of benign from malignant peri-implant effusions owing to the low cell density in the fluid, with a false-negative result being observed with lymphoma-involved effusions at PET.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9a.jpeg" height="1118" width="1002" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9b.jpeg" height="1119" width="668" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9c.jpeg" height="1118" width="906" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9d.jpeg" height="1118" width="1073" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9e.jpeg" height="1390" width="1807" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9f" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9f.jpeg" height="1390" width="1938" aria-labelledby="fig9f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9f</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9g" class="graphic" aria-label="Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm3 low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm3 polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. (a) Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. (b) On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. (c, d) Standard (c) and high-power (d) photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (e) On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). (f) Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). (g) Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig9g.jpeg" height="942" width="1796" aria-labelledby="fig9g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9g</span>. Internal mammary lymphadenopathy (false-positive result at anatomic-functional imaging) in BIA-ALCL in a 50-year-old woman who underwent left mastectomy and insertion of a breast implant (acellular dermal matrix Mentor 350-cm<sup>3</sup> low-height high-profile [Johnson &amp; Johnson, New Brunswick, NJ]) for grade 3 intraductal carcinoma. The following year, she underwent right mastectomy with insertion of a 350-cm<sup>3</sup> polyurethane implant. Six years later, she presented with a swollen left breast reconstruction and discoloration of the lower half of the skin paddle. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows a large corpuscolate effusion (arrow) surrounding the left breast implant. <b>(b)</b> On a sagittal T2-weighted MR image, the left implant appears intact. The seroma demonstrates heterogeneity in the component adjacent to the nipple area and the subcutaneous tissues (arrow). Under US guidance, 250 mL of complex fluid was aspirated from the left breast. The diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. <b>(c, d)</b> Standard <b>(c)</b> and high-power <b>(d)</b> photomicrographs of the left capsulectomy specimen show a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(e)</b> On an axial FDG PET/CT image, besides the known photopenic left breast seroma (red arrow), a low-volume nonspecific mildly avid (maximum standardized uptake value [SUVmax] = 3) right internal mammary chain lymph node is seen (blue arrow). <b>(f)</b> Follow-up axial PET/CT image shows that the lymph node (arrow) is slightly enlarged with a small increase in metabolic activity (SUVmax = 4.5). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image after bilateral removal of the breast implants shows spontaneous resolution of the node. Internal mammary chain lymph nodes are normally observed in a proportion of patients in the context of breast implants and are prone to misinterpretation as being involved (a false-positive result) at CT, MRI, and PET/CT in the context of BIA-ALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig9g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. (a–c) Axial CT (a), axial PET/CT (b), and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET (c) images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in a and b) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. (d) Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig10a.jpeg" height="1162" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial CT <b>(a)</b>, axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b>, and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET <b>(c)</b> images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. <b>(d)</b> Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. (a–c) Axial CT (a), axial PET/CT (b), and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET (c) images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in a and b) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. (d) Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig10b.jpeg" height="1206" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial CT <b>(a)</b>, axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b>, and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET <b>(c)</b> images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. <b>(d)</b> Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. (a–c) Axial CT (a), axial PET/CT (b), and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET (c) images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in a and b) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. (d) Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig10c.jpeg" height="2166" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial CT <b>(a)</b>, axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b>, and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET <b>(c)</b> images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. <b>(d)</b> Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic" aria-label="Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. (a–c) Axial CT (a), axial PET/CT (b), and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET (c) images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in a and b) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. (d) Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig10d.jpeg" height="1041" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Differential diagnosis of a false-positive mass in BIA-ALCL in a 42-year-old woman previously treated for cervical intraepithelial neoplasia who underwent bilateral breast augmentation. Fourteen years later, acute swelling of the left breast developed; US showed a seroma. The left breast capsule with an irregular surface was removed. The histologic diagnosis was ALK-negative BIA-ALCL. PET/CT was performed 2 months later to assess for residual disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial CT <b>(a)</b>, axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b>, and coronal half-body inverse gray-scale PET <b>(c)</b> images show an intensely FDG-avid (SUVmax = 40) rounded 2 × 2-cm soft-tissue mass (blue arrow) in the inferior left breast, medial to the midline and contiguous with the underlying chest wall musculature. The contralateral right breast implant (red arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is unremarkable. Capsulectomy demonstrated large anaplastic lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin. <b>(d)</b> Immunohistochemistry slide shows CD30 positivity. The margins were clear; the treating surgical unit performed a mastectomy (to maximize the chance of local disease control), which was followed by three cycles of combination chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisolone (CHOP). Apparent increased PET activity in the postoperative surgical bed may reflect false-positive activity (including inflammatory or infective change) and requires corroboration with histologic biopsy results for a diagnosis of lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagnosis, staging, response assessment, and surveillance strategies for the peri-implant effusion and mass-forming or distant disease subtypes of BIA-ALCL. Original pathway diagram summarizes patient management paradigms for accurate staging and response assessment with optimal use of currently available imaging and health care resources. FNA = fine-needle aspiration; NTAP = neck, thorax, abdomen, pelvis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig11.jpeg" height="2317" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Diagnosis, staging, response assessment, and surveillance strategies for the peri-implant effusion and mass-forming or distant disease subtypes of BIA-ALCL. Original pathway diagram summarizes patient management paradigms for accurate staging and response assessment with optimal use of currently available imaging and health care resources. <i>FNA</i> = fine-needle aspiration; <i>NTAP</i> = neck, thorax, abdomen, pelvis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). (a) Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. (b) Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. (c) Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as b) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig12a.jpeg" height="1113" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(b)</b> Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as <b>b</b>) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). (a) Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. (b) Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. (c) Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as b) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig12b.jpeg" height="1113" width="1588" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(b)</b> Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as <b>b</b>) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in Fig 1e, 1f). (a) Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. (b) Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. (c) Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as b) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig12c.jpeg" height="1113" width="862" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Anatomic detail of BIA-ALCL with chest wall invasion in a 29-year-old woman who underwent bilateral breast augmentation with TRF-520 implants (Allergan) and developed a right upper inner breast lump 3 years after surgery (same patient as in <a href="#fig1e">Fig 1e</a>, <a href="#fig1f">1f</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial color flow US image shows a corresponding 3-cm mass (arrow) along the edge of the external capsule of the implant at the 2-o’clock position. <b>(b)</b> Axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with breath holding 4 months later shows irregular surface of the implant (blue arrow) and rapid enlargement (estimated at 7 cm axially) of the lobulated mass (red arrow), which is characterized by a central necrotic area. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) image (obtained at the same time as <b>b</b>) shows the mass (arrow) infiltrating the pectoralis major muscle and threatening the intercostal muscles. Biopsy demonstrated large atypical CD30-positive cells infiltrating the fibrous tissue. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Because progressive (primary refractory) disease with extensive chest wall involvement and pleural effusion occurred despite CHOP therapy, second-line therapy with brentuximab was administered, with complete imaging and clinical response. Adjuvant bilateral total capsulectomy and mastopexy were performed with sentinel lymph node biopsy, which demonstrated negative results. MRI and diagnostic CT provide accurate anatomic detail, including definition of possible chest wall invasion, allowing assessment for operability.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13a.jpeg" height="1132" width="1296" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13b.jpeg" height="1132" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13c.jpeg" height="939" width="1477" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13d.jpeg" height="939" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13e" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13e.jpeg" height="787" width="1287" aria-labelledby="fig13e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13e</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13f" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13f.jpeg" height="795" width="1524" aria-labelledby="fig13f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13f</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13g" class="graphic" aria-label="False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a BRCA2 mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). (a) Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). (b) Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. (c) Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. (d) High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). (e) Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). (f) Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. (g) Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (6,45)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig13g.jpeg" height="1866" width="883" aria-labelledby="fig13g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13g</span>. False-positive postoperative findings at surveillance imaging for BIA-ALCL in a 39-year-old woman who was a <i>BRCA2</i> mutation carrier. She underwent bilateral prophylactic risk-reducing mastectomy with immediate reconstruction and exchange of implants twice in 8 years. After the last operation, a recurrent seroma developed around the left breast reconstruction (TRF-520 implants [Allergan]). <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows that the left breast implant is intact, but there is some irregularity of its surface (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image shows the prosthesis surrounded by a corpuscolate seroma (arrow). Two hundred twenty milliliters of clear yellow fluid was aspirated and sent for microbiology and pathology evaluation. The final diagnosis was BIA-ALCL. Left capsulectomy and capsulotomy and removal of the implant were performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the specimen shows a dense infiltrate of large atypical lymphoid cells enmeshed in fibrin lining the inner aspect of the capsule, with no capsular invasion. <b>(d)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows that the large atypical cells have abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with pleomorphic and at times indented nuclei (arrows). <b>(e)</b> Follow-up axial FDG PET/CT image shows postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image 7 months later after right capsulectomy shows resolution of the postsurgical inflammatory changes in the left chest wall. <b>(g)</b> Coronal inverse gray-scale maximum intensity projection (MIP) PET image shows no evidence of distant disease. Inflammatory change (false-positive finding) is typically observed at PET/CT of the postsurgical bed. We advocate no routine imaging surveillance follow-up in treated BIA-ALCL, analogous to surveillance imaging guidelines for other NHL histologic subtypes (<a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>,<a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig13g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Research paradigm for diagnosis, staging, response assessment, and surveillance strategies for the peri-implant effusion and mass-forming or distant disease subtypes of BIA-ALCL. Original pathway diagram for future practice shows use of whole-body (WB) DWI for staging and response assessment. This potential approach requires research validation. FNA = fine-needle aspiration."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190198/asset/images/large/rg.2020190198.fig14.jpeg" height="2162" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Research paradigm for diagnosis, staging, response assessment, and surveillance strategies for the peri-implant effusion and mass-forming or distant disease subtypes of BIA-ALCL. Original pathway diagram for future practice shows use of whole-body <i>(WB)</i> DWI for staging and response assessment. This potential approach requires research validation. <i>FNA</i> = fine-needle aspiration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190198&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Keech JA Jr, Creech BJ. Anaplastic T-cell lymphoma in proximity to a saline-filled breast implant. <em>Plast Reconstr Surg</em> 1997;100(2):554–555.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/00006534-199708000-00065">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9252643/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Anaplastic+T-cell+lymphoma+in+proximity+to+a+saline-filled+breast+implant&amp;author=JA+Keech&amp;author=BJ+Creech&amp;publication_year=1997&amp;journal=Plast+Reconstr+Surg&amp;pages=554-555&amp;doi=10.1097%2F00006534-199708000-00065&amp;pmid=9252643">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">American Society of Plastic Surgeons. BIA-ALCL Physician Resources. <a href="https://www.plasticsurgery.org/for-medical-professionals/health-policy/bia-alcl-physician-resources">https://www.plasticsurgery.org/for-medical-professionals/health-policy/bia-alcl-physician-resources</a>. Published 2019. Accessed October 15, 2019.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=BIA-ALCL+Physician+Resources&amp;author=American+Society+of+Plastic+Surgeons">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">U.S. Food and Drug Administration. Medical Device Reports of Breast Implant-Associated Anaplastic Large Cell Lymphoma. <a href="https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/breast-implants/medical-device-reports-breast-implant-associated-anaplastic-large-cell-lymphoma">https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/breast-implants/medical-device-reports-breast-implant-associated-anaplastic-large-cell-lymphoma</a>. Published 2019. Accessed October 15, 2019.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Medical+Device+Reports+of+Breast+Implant-Associated+Anaplastic+Large+Cell+Lymphoma&amp;author=U.S.+Food+and+Drug+Administration">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Loch-Wilkinson A, Beath KJ, Knight RJW, et al. Breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma in Australia and New Zealand: high-surface-area textured implants are associated with increased risk. <em>Plast Reconstr Surg</em> 2017;140(4):645–654.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/PRS.0000000000003654">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28481803/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Breast+implant-associated+anaplastic+large+cell+lymphoma+in+Australia+and+New+Zealand%3A+high-surface-area+textured+implants+are+associated+with+increased+risk&amp;author=A+Loch-Wilkinson&amp;author=KJ+Beath&amp;author=RJW+Knight&amp;publication_year=2017&amp;journal=Plast+Reconstr+Surg&amp;pages=645-654&amp;doi=10.1097%2FPRS.0000000000003654&amp;pmid=28481803">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">5.</div><div id="r5" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">de Boer M, van Leeuwen FE, Hauptmann M, et al. Breast implants and the risk of anaplastic large-cell lymphoma in the breast. <em>JAMA Oncol</em> 2018;4(3):335–341.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamaoncol.2017.4510">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed">